   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1843-XX_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <p>
               <note>78</note>
               <lb/>
               that I could not help coveting the<lb/>
               like for you - But upon inquiry<lb/>
               I find wages impracticable -<lb/>
               a good cook &amp; housekeeper from <add>£</add>25 to <add>£</add>30<lb/>
               a Butler such as I see here <hi rend="underline">good</hi> 40 - not a<lb/>
               <add>penny less - finding their own clothes</add>
               <lb/>
               a housemaid - good - not under 10 and<lb/>
               usually from ten to <hi rend="underline">fourteen</hi>
               <lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">finding</hi> their own tea &amp; sugar -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>- I must put all this as you<lb/>
               will say out of my head - &amp; so I will if<lb/>
               I can - But I do so long for your<lb/>
               comfort dear mother that you<lb/>
               had even two good servants<lb/>
               cook - &amp; butler - for credit - care<lb/>
               and really Economy as well as comfort<lb/>
               - if one could but afford it - "I beg<lb/>
               your pardon" - "for what what my dear?"<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>Thank you for the lines you<lb/>
               crammed in at the end of your letter<lb/>
               about the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#OHigW1" cert="medium">Lord Bishop Higgins</persName> &amp;<lb/>
               the Pope &amp; the prayers of his Holiness<lb/>
                  for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#OConD2">OConnell</persName> - this made <unclear>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoilJ1">Mr <choice>
                        <orig>Moil<lb/>
                  liet</orig>
                        <reg>Moilliet</reg>
                     </choice>
                  </persName>
               </unclear> laugh till he cried - he could not <add>have</add>
               <lb/>
               believed it he said unless it had<lb/>
               come from such good authority<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>It is very amusing to me to hear<lb/>
               his odd ignorant, inconsistent, <choice>
                  <orig>bene-<lb/>
                  volent</orig>
                  <reg>benevolent</reg>
               </choice>, intolerant, liberal almost <choice>
                  <orig>ra-<lb/>
                     dical</orig>
                  <reg>radical</reg>
               </choice> opinions all mixed up together<lb/>
               frying &amp; hissing <add>within him</add> &amp; boiling over sometimes<lb/>
               - He conceives that <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> is still<lb/>
               a dreadfully persecuted country - treated<lb/>
               quite as a conquered country - shockingly<lb/>
               therefore he cannot but wish for the repeal<lb/>
               of the Union to set Ireland free at last<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1843-XX_page02.jpg"/>
                  - It is so horridly unjust he says that she <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>
               <lb/>
                  should be <hi rend="underline">oppressed</hi> by the English debt<lb/>
                  But then I tell him <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName> does not<lb/>
                  tax us - and opens her markets to us<lb/>
                  &amp;c But still says he she is insulted<lb/>
                  as a conquered country has no parliament of<lb/>
                  her own - &amp; was taken from her by the Union<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>There must be a repeal of that Union<lb/>
               stamping about on the hearth<lb/>
               (and the tear full in his eye about nothing)<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>- Then your Irish tenants are so<lb/>
               cruelly oppressed by your Irish landlord<lb/>
               There must be a redress of grievances<lb/>
               &amp; fixity of tenure<lb/>
               Stay till you hear more - A<lb/>
               commission is now appointed in<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <orig>Parl</orig>
                  <reg>Parliament</reg>
               </choice>? &amp; you will find that our tenants<lb/>
                  rights are respected &amp; that they may<lb/>
               have fixity of tenure without more ado<lb/>
               If you mean certainly that their<lb/>
               farms will be relet to them &amp; <unclear>input</unclear> allowed<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>If you mean by fixity of tenure that<lb/>
               all the tenants sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> remain in fixed possession<lb/>
               of the landlords property the landlord<lb/>
               must have <unclear>Income</unclear> because they<lb/>
               cannot live upon nothing - Both<lb/>
               catholic &amp; protestant landlords must go<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>At the word <hi rend="underline">Catholic</hi> quite a<lb/>
               new train of ideas are in <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoilJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Moilliets</persName>
               <lb/>
               mind - Observe the Catholics are<lb/>
               his great plagues at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Geneva_SZ">Geneva</placeName> where<lb/>
               they are now all at sixes &amp; sevens<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>He cant abide <add>a</add> Catholic priest - he<lb/>
               turns short round, <del/> and<lb/>
               throws his hands out as if pushing<lb/>
               the idea of a Catholic priest from him<lb/>
               with abhorrence - But the seven millions<lb/>
               of Catholic poor I own he thinks should have<lb/>
               perfect toleration <add>&amp; emancipation</add> I tell him they have - only<lb/>
               May none can be <choice>
                  <orig>Arch<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>Archbishop</reg>
               </choice> of <choice>
                  <orig>Cant<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>
                  </orig>
                  <reg>Canterbury</reg>
               </choice> or York<lb/>
               and cannot be Generals <unclear/> of the armies<lb/>
            </p>
         </div>
